Finally, we study the fraction of active (flippable) spins ${f_t(N)}$ as a function of time $t$. 
Figure \ref{fig:FLS} is a log-log plot of ${f_t(N)}$ vs.\ $t$. We find that for the first 10 sweeps, ${f_t(N)}$ has a power law decay.   At longer times the curves fall much more steeply.  However, for intermediate times and the larger system sizes there appears to be a flattening before the steep fall-off.   Thus the asymptotic behavior in time for  ${f_t(N)}$ in the limit $N \rightarrow \infty$ is not clear.  A power law  ${f_t(N)} = (1/2)(t +1)^{-1.52}$ in the range $0 \leq t \leq 10$ is a good fit to the data for all values of $N$.  
